Overview

This project connects the HLK-LD2410C millimeter-wave radar to a NodeMCU (ESP8266), which decodes movement distance data and then transmits it via UART to an Arduino Mega 2560.

The NodeMCU acts as a data parser and serial bridge, converting raw HLK UART frames into a simple ASCII message format readable by the Mega.
The Mega then displays the received movement distance (MM) and detection flag (ANY) on the Serial Monitor.

üîå Pin Configuration
üü© NodeMCU (ESP8266) Connections
Component	                                                        NodeMCU Pin	                                                    Description
HLK TX	                                                            D7 (GPIO13)	                                    NodeMCU receives radar UART data
HLK RX (optional)	                                                  D8 (GPIO15)	                                NodeMCU transmits (for configuration if needed)
NodeMCU D8 (TX after swap)	                                    ‚Üí Mega RX1 (Pin 19)	                                    Sends decoded data to Arduino Mega
NodeMCU VIN	                                                    ‚Üê Mega 5 V	                                                  Power supply from Mega
NodeMCU GND	                                                 Common Ground with Mega & HLK	                                      Shared ground
HLK VCC	                                                            5 V (from Mega)	                                                Radar power
HLK GND	                                                        Common Ground	                                                      Shared ground

‚ö†Ô∏è Ensure all devices share a common ground. Power NodeMCU through VIN (5 V) ‚Äî not 3.3 V.

üü© Arduino Mega 2560 Connections
Connection	                                                      Arduino Pin	                                                      Description
From NodeMCU D8 (TX)	                                            RX1 (Pin 19)	                                            Serial1 input from NodeMCU
GND	                                                                Common	                                                Shared with NodeMCU and HLK

- The HLK sensor continuously sends binary UART data (default 256000 baud)
- The NodeMCU parses that data, extracts move distance, applies a 50 cm threshold, and sends formatted ASCII strings to the Mega in this form:

Output: S=B,MM=47,ANY=1

The Arduino Mega reads the line, extracts values, and prints them to the Serial Monitor.

üß† Data Format
Field	                                                    Meaning
S=B	                                Source identifier (B = Back sensor, can be customized)
MM	                                  Movement distance (in cm) extracted from HLK frame
ANY	                                  Binary flag (1 if object ‚â§ 50 cm, else 0)

üíª NodeMCU Code Summary
- Uses Serial.swap() to reassign UART0: RX ‚Üí D7, TX ‚Üí D8, freeing the USB UART.
- Reads binary data frames from HLK-LD2410C.
- Parses header (F4 F3 F2 F1) and tail (F8 F7 F6 F5).
- Extracts move distance using layout offsets.
- Outputs formatted ASCII message to Mega.

üíª Arduino Mega Code Summary
Listens on Serial1 (RX1=Pin 19) at the same baud rate as HLK/NodeMCU (typically 256000 bps).
Parses the incoming S=B,MM=<cm>,ANY=<0|1> string.
Displays readable values on the Serial Monitor (115200 bps).

üßæ Results and Features
‚úÖ Real-time distance measurement from HLK-LD2410C via NodeMCU
‚úÖ Reliable UART-to-UART bridge from NodeMCU ‚Üí Arduino Mega
‚úÖ Clean, readable ASCII output for integration with other systems
‚úÖ Ideal for Smart Bicycle EWS, collision detection, or IoT presence sensing

